<p>The <a href="/w/cpp/language/new" title="cpp/language/new">new-expression</a> is the only way to create an object or an array of objects with dynamic storage duration, that is, with lifetime not restricted to the scope in which it is created. A new-expression obtains storage by calling an allocation function. A <a href="/w/cpp/language/delete" title="cpp/language/delete">delete-expression</a> destroys a most derived object or an array created by a new-expression and calls the deallocation function. The default allocation and deallocation functions, along with related functions, types, and objects, are declared in the header <code>&lt;new&gt;</code>. 
